Excludable sources and ambiences.

An excludable source and an excludable ambience are sound objects with a hole cut in them. They work like an ordinary sound source or ambience — a looping clip filling a rectangular area — but they add a second rectangle, the exclusion zone, where the sound goes silent. Step into that inner pocket and the audio cuts out; step back out of it and the audio returns. They're the way to lay ambience across a region while keeping one spot inside it quiet, like a noisy street with a hushed doorway, or a humming room with a soundproof booth in the corner. Both are always built as an area, never a single tile, since a hole only makes sense inside a region.

How an excludable object works.

Both take a looping clip — chosen from the musics or sources library, the library first and then the clip — and play it over a main rectangular area at a volume and pitch you set, filling the area at full volume and fading past its edges. They also take a second rectangle, the exclusion zone, placed anywhere you like. While the player stands inside the exclusion zone, the sound is silenced; the moment they leave it, the sound comes back. On 3d maps both rectangles span height as well, each between its own minimum and maximum z.

Source versus ambience.

Both fall silent inside the exclusion pocket. They differ in how they behave everywhere else, exactly as a plain source and ambience do:

An excludable source plays continuously and is heard by proximity. Outside the exclusion pocket the player hears it whether they're inside the main area or approaching it from beyond the edges, louder up close and fainter with distance — it only ever goes quiet inside the pocket.
An excludable ambience plays only while the player is inside the main area and outside the exclusion pocket. Leaving the main area silences it just as stepping into the pocket does, and it resumes when the player is back inside the area but out of the pocket.

Reach for a source when the sound should carry across the world with just one dead spot carved out of it, and an ambience when the sound belongs to one region and should also have a quiet pocket within it.

Excludable fields.

Both forms take the following:

Main area. A minimum and maximum x and a minimum and maximum y (and a minimum and maximum z on 3d maps), marking the rectangle the sound fills.
Exclusion area. A minimum and maximum exclusion x and a minimum and maximum exclusion y (and a minimum and maximum exclusion z on 3d maps), marking the inner rectangle where the sound goes silent.
Category. Which library the clip comes from: musics for soundtrack pieces, or sources for general source sounds.
Sound (a folder name from the chosen library's list, or none). The looping clip the object plays. Pick none for a silent object.
Volume. How loud the loop plays, from -100 at the quietest up to 0 at full volume.
Pitch. The playback pitch as a flat value, defaulting to 100 for the clip's natural pitch and ranging from 5 to 1000 — lower values play deeper and slower, higher values brighter and faster.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the sound list, the volume slider, or the pitch slider is focused in the form, press space to start a looping preview of the highlighted clip, and press space again to stop it. Adjusting the volume or pitch slider while the preview is playing updates it live, so you can set the level and pitch by ear before placing the object.

Authoring excludable objects by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, an excludable source is written under the name excludable_source and an excludable ambience under the name excludable_ambience; everything else about the two lines is identical. The line is excludable_source minx maxx miny maxy category sound volume pitch exminx exmaxx exminy exmaxy, where the first rectangle is the main area and the trailing four numbers are the exclusion area. On 3d maps a minimum and maximum z follow each rectangle's y pair: excludable_source minx maxx miny maxy minz maxz category sound volume pitch exminx exmaxx exminy exmaxy exminz exmaxz. The category is the literal word musics or sources, the sound must match a folder name in that library or the word none, and the volume and pitch are numbers.
